Creating a file in .NET 4.x and reading it in .NET Core doesn&#39;t work yet though. There&#39;s even a [Github issue about this](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/issues/35629) that isn&#39;t fixed yet. 

Using [BinaryFormatter is discouraged](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.runtime.serialization.formatters.binary.binaryformatter?view=netframework-4.8) due to security and compatibility issues. This class can deserialize anything, including unexpected or malicious types, based on the file&#39;s contents. That&#39;s what causes this compatibility problem too - the deserializer produced a new `System.String` that doesn&#39;t match the .NET Core runtime&#39;s types. 

There are more mundane problems too - adding or removing a property can cause compatibility issues because the type created by BinaryFormatter won&#39;t match the type used by the rest of the application. The issue is described in [Version Tolerant Serialization](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/serialization/version-tolerant-serialization).

I wouldn&#39;t hold my breath waiting for a cross-framework fix for this. The type is unpopular, actively discouraged and rarely used which means that there will be few volunteers to fix it. Core team employees in the meantime have higher priority issues like gRPC and stabilizing popular stacks like WinForms and WPF.

